### Modules in Rust

Modules organize code into logical groups and control visibility (public/private). They are the foundation of Rust's module system.

---

### Module Visibility

| Keyword | Visibility |
|---------|------------|
| `pub` | Public (accessible outside module) |
| `pub(crate)` | Public within the crate |
| `pub(super)` | Public to parent module |
| Default | Private to parent module |

---

### Module Organization

```rust
// In lib.rs or main.rs
mod math {
    // Private by default
    fn internal_helper() { }

    // Public function
    pub fn add(a: i32, b: i32) -> i32 {
        a + b
    }

    // Public submodule
    pub mod advanced {
        pub fn power(base: i32, exp: u32) -> i32 {
            base.pow(exp)
        }
    }
}

// Using modules
use math::add;
use math::advanced::power;

// Re-exporting
pub use math::advanced::power;

// File-based module
// math.rs or math/mod.rs
// mod math;  // imports from math.rs
```

> **Key Point:** Everything in Rust is private by default. Use `pub` to make items visible outside their module. The module tree starts at the crate root (lib.rs or main.rs). Use `use` to bring items into scope.

codeExample:
mod greetings {
    pub fn hello() -> String {
        String::from("Hello!")
    }

    pub fn goodbye() -> String {
        String::from("Goodbye!")
    }

    fn internal() -> String {
        String::from("Internal only")
    }
}

fn main() {
    println!("{}", greetings::hello());
    println!("{}", greetings::goodbye());
    // greetings::internal();  // ERROR: private function
}
